			<p id="functions" align="right"><a href="#artBookmarks" onclick="artShareLinks.expandit(0); return true" class="share">Share<span> |</span></a><a href="javascript:window.print()" class="print">Print</a></p>
			<p class="contentHeading"><span><a href="/science/news/?site=science">News in Science</a> </span></p>
<!--end:ggEndIf--><h1><span>Nematodes reveal the secret to a long life</span></h1>
<p class="byline"><span class="date">Thursday, 12 May 2011</span> Clare Pain<br><span class="author">ABC</span></p><hr noshade size="1" class="lineBreakTop" /><div class="right">
<div id="storyRelatedMedia">
<div id="storyPhotos" class="photo imgBox"><a id="storyPhotosLink" href="http://www.abc.net.au/reslib/201105/r765926_6479047.jpg"><img id="storyPhotosImg" src="http://www.abc.net.au/reslib/201105/r765926_6479047.jpg" alt="Caenorhabditis elegans" class="featureImg"></a><p id="storyPhotosCaption" class="caption">The research may explain why small eaters live longer <em>(Source: Matthew Gill)</em></p>
</div><script type="text/javascript"><!--
						if (typeof showPhotos == 'function') showPhotos('3214128-mediarss.xml');
						--></script></div>
<div id="related">
<h3>Related Stories</h3>
<ul>
<li><a href="/science/articles/2010/07/12/2950957.htm">Longevity gene may also boost memory</a>, Science Online, 12 Jul 2010</li>
<li><a href="/science/articles/2008/08/11/2331197.htm">Scientists stop the ageing process</a>, Science Online, 11 Aug 2008</li>
<li><a href="/science/articles/2007/05/03/1913183.htm">The gene for longevity, if you're a worm</a>, Science Online, 10 Nov 2008</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<p class="first"><span class="slug">Slowing down</span> Tiny worms have revealed a class of signalling molecules that could play a key role in extending lifespan.</p>
<p>Dr Matthew Gill and other scientists working at the <a href="http://www.buckinstitute.org/" target="_blank">Buck Institute for Research on Aging</a> in the United States have been studying nematode worms: tiny transparent worms (only 1 millimetre long) that live in the soil. </p>
<p>They have discovered that molecules called N-acylethanolamines (NAEs) must be at low levels for nematodes to enjoy longevity. </p>
<p>The findings are reported in this week's edition of <em><a href="http://dx.doi.org/10.1038/nature10007" target="_blank">Nature</a></em>.</p>
<p>It is known that restricting the diet of certain animals leads to a longer lifespan. Effects have been found in organisms including yeast, fruit flies and mice, as well as in nematode worms. Research is ongoing in humans, but it will take decades to get these results.  </p>
<p>"Nematodes live for only about 20 days, so it's much quicker to do lifespan research in them than in say, mice, which live three to five years", says Gill, "plus they have been used as a model animal for research since the 1970s so we know a huge amount about them."</p>
<p>Gill's nematodes are cultured in Petri dishes and live off a "bacterial lawn" of <em>E. coli</em>. Nematodes given a lower concentration of <em>E. coli</em> live about 33 per cent longer than ones given abundant food. </p>
<p>"When worms are put on a really thick bacterial lawn so they can gorge every minute of their lives, they look less healthy than ones put on a plate with hardly any food. These restricted worms look very robust and healthy," says Gill.</p><h3>Why does dietary restriction work?</h3><p>The team at the Buck Institute wondered whether NAEs might play a role. These lipid molecules are known to be involved in controlling feeding behaviours in mammals, fish and simple invertebrates. </p>
<p>They discovered that levels of NAEs were unusually low for worms on the restricted diet. Furthermore, when the scientists used mutant worms that had been manipulated to have low levels of NAEs, the mutant worms lived longer, even on a normal diet.</p>
<p>"We think the low levels of NAEs signal the organism to change its physiology to a very different state that is adapted to a low level of food", says Gill, "but that is conjecture at the moment"</p>
<p>The work is significant because it links NAEs with lifespan extension in one of the most useful models for lifespan research - the humble nematode. </p>
<p>No doubt researchers exploring longevity in other animals will be looking to see whether NAEs are important there too. </p>
<p class="tags"><strong>Tags: </strong><a href="/science/tag/browse.htm?site=science&amp;topic=latest&amp;tag=health">health</a>, <a href="/science/tag/browse.htm?site=science&amp;topic=latest&amp;tag=medical-research">medical-research</a>, <a href="/science/tag/browse.htm?site=science&amp;topic=latest&amp;tag=genetics">genetics</a></p><!-- footer start -->

				
					
					
